validateConfig() is paired with a stricter production-only configuration validation flow: Production Azure configuration now uses fail-fast validation—required environment variables throw errors if missing in production, preventing use of insecure defaults and accidental Azure resource overwrites. The introduced validateProductionConfig() method (in azure.config.ts) enforces configuration integrity before application startup, ensuring all environment variables are set. This now includes additional checks for critical environment variables like PUBLIC_SITE_URL (required for OAuth), and AZURE_STORAGE_CONTAINER_NAME (for storage) to guarantee proper production setup. The method throws explicit errors if required values are missing in production, while warnings or safe defaults are allowed in development for clarity and safety. Example:
```javascript
// Validate Azure configuration for production environments
try {
  if (typeof process !== 'undefined' && process.env) {
    const { azureConfig } = await import('./src/config/azure.config.ts')
    azureConfig.validateProductionConfig()
    console.log('✅ Azure configuration validation passed')
  }
} catch (error) {
  if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production') {
    console.error('❌ Azure Configuration Error:', error.message)
    process.exit(1)
  } else {
    console.warn('⚠️  Azure Configuration Warning:', error.message)
  }
}
```
Context: Enforcing fail-fast validation for all critical production variables (including OAuth and storage config) prevents misconfiguration of key services and improves deployment security.

