Ref access in useEffect cleanup is fixed by capturing the ref value within the effect's scope before the cleanup:
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  const timeouts = timeoutRefs.current
  return () => {
    timeouts.forEach(clearTimeout)
  }
}, [])
```
This avoids stale closure issues per React exhaustive-deps rules in hooks. Context: captures the latest ref in React useEffect hook cleanups to prevent logic bugs and aligns with React's guidance on effect dependency handling.

Solution Pattern for useEffect dependencies:
```tsx
// Use refs to capture latest function references
const fnRef = useRef(fn)
fnRef.current = fn

useEffect(() => {
  fnRef.current()
}, [stableValue]) // Use stable primitive instead of changing objects
```
Context: This pattern fixes unstable useEffect dependency arrays by using useRef to hold function references and only stable primitives in dependency arrays, preventing unnecessary re-renders. This technique is foundational for optimal React effect management and prevents accidental infinite re-renders in functional components.

