Astro 5.x's API route typing has a critical bug: the `APIContext` type no longer includes the required `request` property due to broken generic type inheritance. This breaks TypeScript type checking for API routes and causes module resolution errors. To ensure compatibility and correct typing, do not import `APIContext` from 'astro'. Instead, define a custom base interface (e.g., `BaseAPIContext`) that explicitly extends all necessary context properties for your API handlers. Example implementation:
```
interface BaseAPIContext<
  Props extends Record<string, unknown> = Record<string, unknown>,
  Params extends Record<string, string | undefined> = Record<string, string | undefined>
> {
  request: Request;
  url: URL;
  params: Params;
  props: Props;
  redirect(path: string, status?: number): Response;
  locals: Record<string, unknown>;
  cookies: {
    get(name: string): { value: string } | undefined;
    set(name: string, value: string, options?: Record<string, unknown>): void;
    delete(name: string, options?: Record<string, unknown>): void;
  };
}
export interface AuthAPIContext<
  Props extends Record<string, unknown> = Record<string, unknown>,
  Params extends Record<string, string | undefined> = Record<string, string | undefined>
> extends BaseAPIContext<Props, Params> {
  locals: BaseAPIContext<Props, Params>["locals"] & {
    user: AuthUser;
  };
  request: Request;
}
```
To fix existing files, replace all usages of Astro-imported types (such as in `src/lib/auth/apiRouteTypes.ts`) with your custom `BaseAPIContext`. After migration, verify fix by running a TypeScript compile check (`pnpm exec tsc --noEmit --skipLibCheck <file>`) and ensure context properties (`request.url`, `request.method`, etc.) are recognized.

Context: This pattern ensures accurate typing for API handlers, avoids broken Astro imports, and preserves type checking as Astro evolves.

